Date: Mon 30 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Russia Journal online, Mon 30 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.russiajournal.com/news/cnewswire.shtml?nw=39075#n39075>

Russia (Dagestan): Buinaksk Quarantined after Outbreak of Hepatitis A
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Emergency officials have quarantined a city in the southern Russian region
of Dagestan after an outbreak of hepatitis at a kindergarten infected
dozens of children, according to a news report today.
42 children from a kindergarten in Buinaksk and one adult have been
hospitalized since 16 Jun 2003 and confirmed to have hepatitis A
infections, Oleg Grekov, an official in the southern regional Emergency
Situations Ministry, told Interfax news agency. Doctors say none are
seriously ill, according to Grekov.
Contaminated water has been confirmed as the source of the outbreak, and
preventative measures are being taken along with the quarantine, Interfax
reported.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Vaccination is an option for control of outbreaks of hepatitis A
infection, but in the case of contamination of water, the ultimate solution
may lie in improved maintenance and re-engineering of basic infrastructure
- Mod.CP]
